","1443":"1443","1388":"1388","1376":"1376","1387":"1387","1354":"1354","1419":"1419","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Paston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk): habitational name, chiefly from Paston in Norfolk, probably derived from an Old English personal name <i>Pæcci</i> (genitive <i>Pæcces</i>) or Old English <i>pæsc(e)</i> (the source of northern English dialect <i>pash</i> ‘puddle’) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","English (West Midlands): sometimes a variant of <b>Patstone</b>, a habitational name chiefly from the lost <i>Padston(e)</i> in Bromsgrove (Worcestershire), and occasionally from Padson in Inwardleigh (Devon). The Worcestershire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Padda</i> (genitive <i>Paddes</i>) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The etymology of the Devon placename is uncertain due to a lack of medieval forms, though an early spelling suggests the final element is Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Clement","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Clemens</i> (genitive <i>Clementis</i>) meaning ‘merciful’. This was borne by several early saints, notably the fourth pope and the early Christian theologian Clement of Alexandria (Titus Flavius Clemens,   ad  ?150–?215 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Clement de Paston II was born in 1355, in Paston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Paston, was 29 and his mother, Elizabeth Staleham, was 30. He married Beatrice de Somerton in 1374, in Paston, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died on 21 September 1388, in his hometown, at the age of 33, and was buried in Paston, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1355–21 September 1388":"1355–21. september 1388","1355–1388":"1355–1388","1357–Female":"1357–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1354–1419":"1354–1419","1376–1443":"1376–1443","1378–1444":"1378–1444","1387–1488":"1387–1488","1326–1393":"1326–1393","1325–1393":"1325–1393","1374":"1374","ABT 1378":"umbes 1378","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1360":"1360","1326":"1326","1325":"1325","21 September 1388":"21. september 1388","1357":"1357","1488":"1488","1444":"1444","1378":"1378","1355":"1355","1443":"1443","1388":"1388","1376":"1376","1387":"1387","1354":"1354","1419":"1419","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1355–21 September 1388":"1355–21. syyskuuta 1388","1355–1388":"1355–1388","1357–Female":"1357–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1354–1419":"1354–1419","1376–1443":"1376–1443","1378–1444":"1378–1444","1387–1488":"1387–1488","1326–1393":"132